The article discusses the joint statement on Syria that condemns the Assad regime's use of chemical weapons and calls for a strong international response. Since its initial release, additional countries have signed on to support the statement, bringing the total to 37 countries. The statement emphasizes the importance of holding the Assad regime accountable and enforcing the international norm against the use of chemical weapons. It also acknowledges the ongoing conflict in Syria, with over 100,000 people killed and millions displaced, and calls for a peaceful political settlement. The signatories commit to supporting efforts to address Syria's chemical weapons stockpiles and provide humanitarian assistance to those affected by the conflict. European signatories will continue to work towards a common European position on the issue.